f)|U.S. Open]]\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|T9\n|CUT\n|style=\"background:#eeeeee;\"|\n|T43\n|CUT\n|T40\n|T36\n|CUT\n|style=\"background:#eeeeee;\"|\n|T24\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|T8\n|T12\n|CUT\n|style=\"background:#eeeeee;\"|\n|CUT\n|-\n|align=left|[[PGA Championship]]\n|style=\"background:#eeeeee;\"|\n|style=\"background:#eeeeee;\"|\n|style=\"background:#eeeeee;\"|\n|T44\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|6\n|style=\"background:yellow;\"|T5\n|T30\n|T17\n|CUT\n|T13\n|style=\"background:#eeeeee;\"|\n|25\n|CUT\n|style=\"background:#eeeeee;\"|\n|style=\"background:#eeeeee;\"|\n|}\n''Note: Ellis never played in [[The Open Championship]].''<br>\n{{legend|yellow|Top 10}}\n{{legend|#eeeeee|Did not play}}\nWD = withdrew<br>\nCUT = missed the half-way cut<br>\n\"T\" indicates a tie for a place\n\n===Summary===\n{| class=wikitable style=text-align:center\n!Tournament !! Wins !! 2nd !! 3rd !! Top-5 !! Top-10 !! Top-25 !! Events !! Cuts made\n|-\n|align=left|[[Masters Tournament]]         || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 ||  3 || 10 || 5\n|-\n|align=left|[[U.S. Open (golf)|U.S. Open]] || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 2 ||  4 || 12 || 7\n|-\n|align=left|[[The Open Championship]]      || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 ||  0 ||  0 || 0\n|-\n|align=left|[[PGA Championship]]           || 0 || 0 || 0 || 1 || 2 ||  5 ||  9 || 7\n|-\n!Totals                                    !! 0 !! 0 !! 0 !! 1 !! 4 !! 12 !! 31 !! 19\n|}\n*Most consecutive cuts made \u2013 8 (1965 Masters \u2013 1967 PGA)\n*Longest streak of top-10s \u2013 1 (four times)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ellis, Wes}}\n[[Category:American male golfers]]\n[[Category:Texas Longhorns men's golfers]]\n[[Category:PGA Tour golfers]]\n[[Category:Golfers from Missouri]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Kansas City, Missouri]]\n[[Category:People from Upper Saddle River, New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Deaths from kidney disease]]\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:1984 deaths]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American  golfer}}\n{{Infobox golfer\n| name              = Wes Ellis\n| image             = \n| imagesize         = \n| caption           = \n| fullname          = Wesley Ellis, Jr.\n| nickname          = \n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|1932|1|27|mf=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Kansas City, Missouri]], U.S.\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|1984|6|4|1932|1|27|mf=y}}\n| death_place       = [[Teaneck, New Jersey]], U.S.\n| height            = {{height|ft=6|in=1}}\n| weight            = {{convert|170|lb|kg st|abbr=on}}\n| nationality       = {{USA}}\n| spouse            = \n| partner           = \n| children          = \n| college           = [[University of Texas]]\n| yearpro           = 1954\n| retired           = <!-- Year retired -->\n| extour            = [[PGA Tour]]\n| prowins           = 15\n| pgawins           = 3\n| otherwins         = 12\n| majorwins         = \n| masters           = T15: 1965\n| usopen            = T8: 1966\n| open              = DNP\n| pga               = T5: 1961\n| wghofid           = \n| wghofyear         = \n| awardssection     = <!-- location of awards page or section -->\n}}\n'''Wesley Ellis, Jr.''' (January 27, 1932 &ndash; June 4, 1984) was an American [[professional golfer]] who played on the [[PGA Tour]] in the 1950s, 1960s and 1970s.\n\nEllis was born in [[Kansas City, Missouri]].<ref name=who>{{cite book |last1=Elliott |first1=Len |first2=Barbara |last2=Kelly |title=Who's Who in Golf |year=1976 |publisher=Arlington House |location=New Rochelle, New York |isbn=0-87000-225-2 |page=[https://archive.org/details/whoswhoingolf00elli/page/58 58] |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/whoswhoingolf00elli/page/58 }}</ref> He attended the [[University of Texas]] in [[Austin, Texas|Austin]] and was a member of the [[golf]] team from 1950&ndash;1952. He won the Massingill Trophy in 1950, and was the individual medalist at the [[Southwest Conference]] Championship in 1952.<ref>[http://www.texassports.com/doc_lib/04-05MGolfHistory_01.pdf '''texassports.com''''' Longhorns in the Pros'']</ref> He graduated in 1953 with a degree in [[zoology]] and turned professional in 1954.<ref name=who/>\n\nEllis won three [[PGA Tour]] events. His first win came at the 1958 [[Canadian Open (golf)|Canadian Open]]. He won by one stroke over [[Jay Hebert]] at the Mayfair Golf and Country Club in [[Edmonton, Alberta]].<ref>[http://www.rcga.org/english/Records/records-details.asp?TID=12 Tournament history from Canadian Open's official site]</ref> His last win came in 1965 at the [[San Diego Open Invitational]] in a playoff against golf legend [[Billy Casper]]. His victory in San Diego was unique in that Ellis used what is commonly known as a \"cross-handed\" putting grip; that is, as a right-handed golfer he kept his left hand below his right.  Ellis had four top-10 finishes in [[Men's major golf championships|major championships]]: a T-9 at the 1956 [[U.S. Open (golf)|U.S. Open]], a T-8 at the 1966 [[U.S. Open (golf)|U.S. Open]], a 6th at the 1960 PGA Championship and a T-5 at the 1961 PGA Championship.\n\nEllis, like many pro golfers of his generation, earned his living primarily as a club pro. For many years he was the head pro at the [[Westchester Country Club]] in [[Rye (city), New York|Rye, New York]] and lived in [[Upper Saddle River, New Jersey]]. He died of kidney disease at the age of 52 at [[Holy Name Medical Center]] in [[Teaneck, New Jersey]].<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9F03E4DE123BF935A35755C0A962948260 Wes Ellis Jr., Leading Golfer In New Jersey Many Years]</ref> He left behind his wife, Marian, and their four children - three daughters and a son.\n\n==Professional wins (15)==\n===PGA Tour wins (3)===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n!No.!!Date!!Tournament!!Winning score!!Margin of victory!!Runner(s)-up\n|-\n| align=center|1 || Aug 23, 1958 || [[Canadian Open (golf)|Canadian Open]] || \u201313 (67-69-65-66=267) || 1 stroke || {{flagicon|USA}} [[Jay Hebert]]\n